76561197992229015,Recommended,244160,26621527,"Posted: 15 November, 2016",all,Dire,"Review is separate for HW 1 and 2.Edit: Homeworld Cataclysm is not part of this remastered edition, since it was developed by another studio and the source code got lost when that went out of business, though there is a mod that is trying to recreate it. At the time of this writing there are no campaign missions though, only skirmishes. Generally there are quite a few total conversions available for skirmish play.Starting off with HW 1.What is Homeworld? It's a space RTS game taking place on a 3 dimensional plane. The maps are always round and you can order your ships ""up"" and ""down"". You can either do that on the normal game screen, which is pretty beautiful in the Remastered edition, or you can bring up a tactical view, which makes it a bit easier. The camera can be freely rotated, but zooming on the other hand is pretty limited and finicky thanks to the 3D aspect. Basically you have to anchor yourself to a unit in order to make the most out of zoom. I guess pro players will mainly use the tac display anyway.So far so good. The interface is pretty decent now (uses the HW 2 one I think). Since there aren't too many different combat units (variation of fighters, bombers, different corvettes, frigates and destroyers as well as a heavy cruiser class), there's not that much micro management, although letting your bombers attack into a multi attack corvette screen is generally considered to be a bad idea, which brings me to my first point of critique: The smaller strike craft feel almost useless later on in the game when destroyers and heavy cruisers are in play and you have some interceptors or stealth fighters or said multi attack corvettes...maybe even drone frigates; there's a lot of sturdier bigger craft that can fulfill the role of anti-fighter and anti-capital better than investing in easily destroyed strike craft. Maybe I'm just bad, definitely possible, but the game also never really explains what benefits certain ""formations"" have. I found out by accident that the ""sphere"" formation is a very bad idea for bombers or fighters, since then they remain stationary and surround the target. They work in conjunction and soak up a lot of the damage, but I found myself replacing them almost constantly, while my bigger craft were mostly untouched.Next critique: The game's UI needs work, seriously. There is a button that displays what kind of craft you have and how many, but there is not button to select these craft. For example, try finding a particular craft, perhaps a resource collector, quickly and you're almost despairing. Speaking of resource collectors: Those buggers never seem to mine automatically, mining takes ages and then you need several resource controllers so they don't have to make the trek back home to your mothership every time, which takes, again, ages. And now we've moved on to the glacial pace this game can evolve to. In the later stages, trying to get your capital ships ANYWHERE can easily take 15 to 20 minutes. They turn and move really really slowly. Yes, that feels epic, but sitting there, waiting quarter of an hour for your ships to go SOMEWHERE is the antithesis of fun.Graphics and sound are pretty decent, however, you are either going to dig or hate the music. It's very space epic-esque.The campaign: Homeworld 1 consists of 16 missions (plus 1 bonus mission that can be found in the extra missions section of the main menu...no idea why they cut this one from the main game, because it fits right in there after mission 4 or so and is actually quite fun). Yes, fun, that's something that varies a lot in this campaign. To understand how the campaign works you need to realize that your goal is to reach your Homeworld (who would have thought) with your Mothership, which cannot move during a mission. Neither does it have any weapons...it just sits there and dies if you're not careful, but who cares, since you rarely get attacked anyway. In any case, your units are permanent, meaning, you take them with you to the next mission if they don't get destroyed. This bit is important, since that can either make the campaign really easy or pretty difficult. There is no difficulty setting, but even so I found myself challenged only a handful of times, but once your armada gets big enough, you should not have any problems at all. Some missions are gimicky, destroying asteroids in your way, moving in areas to avoid radiation. Those are pretty interesting, however, the main issue is that they are either over very quickly (mission 15 literally takes 3 minutes to complete...it's a timed defense mission...what!?!? That should have been part of a bigger mission), or take ages to complete, while you slowly crawl your way forward with your big capital ships of which you can only build so many before the supply limit stops you. Haha, BUT you can always capture more and just get a ridiculously large armada. I think I had 6 Heavy Cruisers, about 8 destroyers and 4 missile destroyers or so...while the game only allows you to have 3, 6 and 2 respectively. Add to that 21 frigates (mostly Ion), a full complement of multi attack corvettes as well as some 70 almost useless strike craft and the enemies did not stand a chance. This is the campaign in a nutshell...the story is pretty threadbare, neatly presented in kinda animtated, but still static images and moderately good voice over (all very downtrodden), but it barely makes sense and you're not even rooting for your own team, you don't feel resentment towards the enemies and there are no characters to identify with. Took me 9 hours to complete, but I had to repeat some stuff, and I guess at least 50% of that time was spent building stuff and waiting. By the way, all unmined resources will automatically transfer to your account after a mission ends, but that doesn't mean you should not replace any lost craft before you jump away, since the next mission can literally drop you in a terrible situation in which you need every ship you can get...Actually that happens quite often...MP is well, I dunno, in HW 1 all races seem to have the same units, so...what's the point besides different designs?All in all HW 1 is a good game, but by no means is it as good as people make it out to be. Unfortunately, if you're into this kind of genre, there's not much else, at least nothing contemporary. Sins of a Solar Empire comes to mind first, but that does not have a campaign either and is a 4x cross breed rather than a true RTS.HW 2:You can expect the same engine and gameplay, but in the campaign as well as the MP there are some serious changes. Also for some reason it just looks better to me. Weird.- I find the campaign to be more engaging to be honest. It's also a bit more cohesive, but it's still space opera and in the end you have more questions than answers- The backdrops are just GORGEOUS- The music is more space nomady than space opera now. Better imho- Small ships (anything not capital or special) are now built as a squad, which makes micro managing your ♥♥♥♥ing fighters and corvettes a lot easier now. Also these ships are now stronger in my opinion. They still die relatively quickly in large fights, but at least they do what they are supposed to do and you can rebuild them quicker.- Resource collectors have taken over the job of the repair corvettes, because resource collection in the campaign doesn't matter anyway- Salvage corvettes are now marine frigates and utterly useless (at least in campaign), since easily destroyed, have to remain stationary for ages to board a vessel and if you already have the max no of vessels you can't claim any more- The game FINALLY auto saves- Missions end automatically, which is bad, since you can no longer replenish your fleet after a big battle, which may mean instant failure of the next mission...stupidAll in all cool campaign, but some design decisions are questionable..."
76561198044299753,Recommended,244160,29408260,Posted: 21 January,all,ZerXen,"Don't look at the number of hours as I have way too many of them off steam ever since 1999 when the first Homeworld brought to the world a new class of RTS and combined it with a great narrative story. In regards to the remastered collection, this is a great value for both old fans and anyone new to Homeworld universe. Two absolutelly great campaigns on modernized engine! RTS games hardly can get much better than this."
,Recommended,244160,27005004,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Katou,"Most real-time strategy games I've played are quite lacking in storytelling.  This is not one of those games.  The original creators of this game, Relic (known for the Company of Heroes and Dawn of War Series) are masters of blending storytelling with real-time strategy while not ignoring the importance of replayability through multiplayer.  Homeworld probably has the most poignant stories I've ever seen without the need for fully animated, fully voiced, lip synched characters.Without revealing the plot, I can tell you that you will feel invested for the safety of the people you are commanding and fighting for.On the more technical side, this game was way ahead of its time in 1999 and holds up well for being nearly 20 years old.  The graphical improvements are a welcome change and a more modern, post-dialup era multiplayer lobby is also welcome.  The voice acting of the narrator, the Mothership's computer, and all your units is outstanding and has not changed from the original.The music also deserves an honorable mention for its ability to add to the feeling of every cutscene, every battle, and every dialogue you encounter.  Top notch stuff.  Especially if you like ambient electronic music.The game is not perfect, however.  Like most RTS games from the 90's, it can be heavy in the micromanaging department.    I also have to dock the games for having somewhat clumsy default controls, a UI that leaves a lot to be desired, and a rather steep learning curve.Another con for some may be the rock-paper-scissor formula that Relic is known for throughout their games.  In this game, there are units that are simply a hard counter to another unit.  In later Relic RTS games, you can see where they added in more unit versatility and soft counters through combined arms.  This leads to some rather spammy gameplay that might be a turn-off for some."
,Not Recommended,244160,14661283,"Posted: 26 February, 2015",all,Rupok,"*Note This is a work in progress review, it will change if devs address the major issues with a few of the mechanics.Even though the graphics, audio and UI redesigns are good I cannot recommend this game right now. It seems like gearbox has broken gameplay mechanics entirely in the remaster of HW1 because of the porting of engine to HW2 engine. Here are just a few of the issues:-The formations are wonky and don't work. You need formations to strike enemy ships effectively. In these games they just use their own flight patterns after they get close to enemy and don't stay in formation.-Game is not using balistic system of the original and instead uses rng, so there are too much hard counters to everything. It is not physics based.-Support frigates are useless unless you get them to follow around and make sure they are healing targets.-Capturing mechanics broken, it is too easy.-salvage corvettes easily capture enemy corvettes because evasion mechanics disabled(they are not part of the rng system)-Salvage ships not showing their beam animation-Why is queues limited to 2?-Collision system is broke, stuff like resource collecters and other ship crash into astroids or other objects and then attempt to push through them instead of moving back.-Some shortcuts do work but its inconsistent, like some keys open certain menus but don't close them when pressed again, while others close when pressed again. Its weird.EDIT:Seems I was wrong with some of the UI mechanics. You can highlight and then choose what ships to select, or you can double click a selected ship and it will highlight all similar ships nearby. You can also select military only ships to be highlighted.This is a very good UI mechanic in the game, just wish they would explain in the tutorials."
