,Recommended,244160,27991500,"Posted: 28 November, 2016",all,100thlurker,"The remastering of the original Homeworld is at heart a modification of Homeworld 2. The places where the second's engines places limitations on the translation of the original are seemingly minor, but have a considerable effect on the gameplay.One example is the way HW1 smallcraft performance is affected. Some of you might recall that scouts and fighters in HW1 behaved in a semi-newtonian fashion, being able to change their orientation without affecting their current direction of travel. This meant that HW1 fighter formations could radically change direction very quickly; for instance fighters attacking a target in X formation would make their pass and then do the ""Starfury Flip"" a bit of a distance away from the target. This is no longer reflected in the Remaster.The result is that fighter formations are more or less useless in Homeworld Remastered. Unlike larger ships, unmodded HW2 fighters generally have to bank and turn as if in atmosphere unlike their predecessors. This means that the entire formation must wheel around to affect a change in direction, which has the affect you might expect on their ability to fight effectively.Small niggles such as these will affect your experience if you look for them. Thankfully you can compare the differences for yourself by trying out the original once again, as it is bundled with the altogether very affordable package. So long as you keep this in mind you really will not be affected, particularly due to Homeworld's gorgeous visuals."
