76561198026846672,Recommended,244160,14765868,"Posted: 6 March, 2015",all,Spark the RPG magnet,"About 20 hours of gameplay. Not including the sequel nor multiplayer.I have some good things to say about this game, including the soundtrack which is by far the best thing (I believe) about this game. The soundtrack absolutely steals the show for me, and like many have said before 'it's like a space opera'.For years on end I was wondering what was so great about homeworld, and really couldn't understand why so many people loved the game. I wasn't able to get my hands on it until now, and instantly fell in love with it. An RTS space game? Count me in!First off, the games included are well worth the price. $35 bucks for TWO games? Including a beta Multiplayer.A space RTS that has probably gone where no other space RTS games have gone before, and it included 3D movement which allows a wide variety of ship maneuvering and freedom most space games don't allow. Ships also have weaknesses on the top bottom and rear, ships take an extra 50% damage if attacked from behind. I like this mechanic, it does something a lot of RTS games haven't explored, which is the flanking damage.I thoroughly enjoyed Sword of the Stars mainly because it felt like a 'total war' in space. But I was disappointed in the lack of a 3 dimensional movement system. I think the best part of my time playing was having two fleets of capital ships and flanking from the top and bottom of enemy ships and engulfing them from all sides. I feel like 3 dimensional movement is not used too much in games and being able to outsmart opponents by descending down upon their ships feels awesome. The game is also very pretty as well, which is important, because battles in this game are absolutely gorgeous and wonderful to watch!The best part of a Space Strategy game is looking at what kinds of ships you could get, there are:Fighters - Basic unit, self explanatoryCorvettes - A heavier ship class, can take more punishment but is slower.Frigates - Capital class shipsDestroyers - Super-Capital class ships that destroy capital ships but are a little less effective vs. strikecraft.Battlecruisers - A Homeworld 2 unit, I think only the Vagyr and Hiigarans can build these.in multiplayer there are four races that play completely differently, and there are a wide variety of units. But I have not played MP much at all.CampaignMissions are very lengthy, depending on how you play and there is a dynamic difficulty that changes the enemy fleet's size depending on your own fleet size. So the better you are at the game, the harder it gets, but the game also has a fleet cap for the enemy fleet in every mission. So if you spent a lot of time salvaging ships over your fleet cap the game might become too easy. The game wasn't that easy for me though, I had to reload several saves.The campaign works a bit like this. Whatever ships you build move on to the next mission. You are the last of the Kushan who were nearly wiped out and are hunted by the Taiidan. From there you must assimilate ships, and reverse engineer them to fight for your claim and survival against the Taiidan Empire. The thing I love the most about the game is how the ships you build move on to the next mission. This is your fleet, and it is shaped by how you play the game, whether you assimilate ships into your fleet or if you build them from scratch, it will show. Is your fleet big? Did you build them from scratch? Or did you assimilate the ships of the Taiidan Empire? At the end of every mission, your fleet will look slightly or more different depending on how you played. You can customize your ship colors as well, through the skirmish match, and the same colors you used in that match will show up in campaign as well.The last few missions I had a tiny bit more ships than the actual fleet cap, and on those missions it spawned fleets nearly twice my size! On some missions I could count over 50 or so capital ships (one of the campaign missions has about over 100 ion cannon frigates I think, didn't have much time to count them all) and on the last mission it spawned about 40 ion cannon and assault frigates backed by destroyers and Heavy Cruisers. Insane!Combined with a challenging difficulty, a steep learning curve, 3D movement, and gorgeous graphics battles can become very hectic and cinematic. I loved every bit and battle I had with the game.I think the best thing about the campaign is seeing the new ships and trying to salvage the Destroyers and Heavy Cruisers in the missions. This game can get very hard if you don't know what you're doing or if you make too many mistakes or don't pay attention to the map. So for you newbies, there's a pause button :DFleet formations work, until you engage the enemy, hopefully it will be patched!"
