76561198001912496,Recommended,244160,14668847,"Posted: 26 February, 2015",all,Herodotus,"Okay, there are some issues with bugs and random crashes for many, but not all. Let's get that out of the way. Does it make the game ""broken""? No, but there ARE issues to be addressed by Gearbox.I won't go into the graphics, story etc. as many reviews have covered this. Let me instead look at the game's 'difficulty' for the new RTS gamer.If you do not strategise and plan in 3D, which was revolutionary at the time (and still is, to my mind) you're going to have a hard time. When I played the original on release in my early thirties I DID find some of the mssions HARD, but then I wasn't used to this type of RTS. The delight was in solving the strategy for myself and finally 'getting it'!I hadn't come across this since ""X-Wing"", which really was a mix of simulator anbd puzzle solving (take out X bombers to pretect Hospital Ship - if you don't in a certain order you fail).So, it all comes down to planning and working out exactly what you need for each mission. ""Tank Rushing"" just will not work, and those with the biggest and baddest fleet, that takes sometimes far too much time and resources, will see you fail time and again (except in skirmish - which we didn't have back then).This game(s) requires thought, and aside from it's beauty (the original still looks marvellous), the strategy required is compelling. You'll hit your keyboard and close the game down in frustration sometimes, but your mind will keep churning over strategies until you come back and try again (and you will).""Brilliant and innovative"" barely describes this title even today."
