,Recommended,244160,17195607,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,Kifa,"What new can I possibly write about Homeworld and its sequel? Unique in time of their original releases, both games still hold up well, after all those years, and prove that design is everything when it comes to creating memorable gaming experiences. Despite somewhat dated appearance both are still very much playable, though I personally have much trouble getting both old versions to run properly on my modern hardware. Thus comes the Remastered Collection, allowing me to again experience both games.You see, I never played Homeworld games specifically for their mechanics, but rather – for one-of-a-kind atmosphere, fantastically designed universe and somewhat mystical approach to space travel. For me, those two games were just wonderful, interactive stories, and strategic gameplay was only a package in which they were delivered. This is probably what makes me oblivious to all the mechanical alterations, and maybe even flaws, that Gearbox has introduced in this remaster. As for the stories themselves I will not say a word – they are to be experienced personally.Mechanically, Homeworld is an RTS in 3D space, to put it bluntly. You collect resources, build units, attack enemies and win missions either by destruction, timer, capture or any combination of those. Sounds pretty standard, right? Well, it is, sort of. Third dimension adds a new element to unit positioning, and in this game it really matters which units attack which targets, in which order and how they are set up in space. You need to apply formations effective in each situation, change unit tactics and generally move around the battlefield a lot more than in a standard RTS. More often than not games also ask for quite a degree of multitasking – luckily in singleplayer active pause comes in handy, allowing to place orders and think out the situation before acting.As I mentioned, not everything works as it should in Homeworld Remastered. Especially in the first campaign it is evident that a lot of things broke when transplanted onto the new game engine. Omission of refuelling mechanic drastically changes the way strike craft operates and renders some ships almost useless.It is worth mentioning though that in the instance of Kadeshi fighters the fuel did seem to run out for them, so it is rather inconsistent.Conversely, in Homeworld 2 Remastered formations seem largely broken. There are more things behaving differently from original, so purists and hardcore game fans will be put off, but I – for reasons I mentioned above – enjoyed both campaigns to the fullest. Sure, sometimes I had to put more clickwork to make things fly around as intended, however none of the issues would break the game for me.I have not tested the multiplayer component yet, though I am not much of an online gamer so I might never do that actually. Keep in mind that my review is from single player standpoint only. Also I’d like to point out that the lack of Cataclysm in the remaster is a bit disappointing, but maybe, just maybe, some day they will be able to release that too.From a visual standpoint, the game is the definition of what a “remaster” should be. Every model in the game has been reworked from ground up and even the smallest fighters are now more detailed than largest capital ships in the original Homeworld. Great texturework is accompanied by a set of subtle effects like volumetric lighting, multiple-source dynamic shadows and lighting, depth of field and of course high resolution support. Animatics between missions have been re-drawn in high definition and compressed with quality in mind. Homeworld Remastered Collection is simply gorgeous. Stunning visuals are accompanied by great voiceover and absolutely stunning soundtrack, which is as far as I’m concerned absolutely unique in games world, combining ethnic and symphonic themes into one. The game simply feels majestic at times. Audio has been, of course, cleaned up since the original.Overall, there is really no reason one should not get Homeworld Remastered Collection. It is a great re-release of two great real time strategy games, providing many hours of gameplay even in single player mode, though I'll state this again - for me most important here are the epic story and atmosphere. There is already extensive mod support too, meaning that fans of altering the game will be able to find something for themselves, and purists should be able to ‘fix’ the game soon enough. In terms of presentation it’s flawless. If it was flawless mechanically, we’d have an absolute remaster benchmark on our hands. As it is, it’s just great."
76561198168937057,Recommended,244160,17281223,"Posted: 29 July, 2015",all,bocsuit,"The game is good but some how Hmw1 crashes to much, any updates that will fix it? It crashes on the tutorial."
