,Recommended,244160,16853636,"Posted: 2 July, 2015",all,ShutterCat,"This review is based on comparing the experiences of playing Homeworld GOTY edition when it came out ~1999 and playing Homeworld 1 Remastered.It's gorgeous. Classic was beautiful for its time and the sensation of depth and scale is preserved in this graphical update. The light rays made my jaw drop when I turned them on, but now I think they make space feel small, like the inside of a cloud or a slightly murky pond. I'm still trying out different combinations of the ""modern"" graphics toys Blur, Bloom, Depth, and Rays.The ""waypoint"" navigation from Cataclysm is present, and useful for such things as scout patrols and correctly orienting frigate/capital formations.The gorgeously spare UI of HW classic is gone, replaced with the festoon of boxes typical of the genre. Not all bad news however: the selected unit list in the lower left is good for rapidly inspecting the health of your fighter squadrons and issuing individual dock orders. Replacing the Build, Research, and Launch full screen pages of Classic with a right-hand pane greatly enhances situational awareness and saves me from toggling in and out of the build manager over and over while I try to figure out what I'm still short on.The option to cancel a hyperspace command while the ships are maneuvering into formation is a welcome addition.Formations are broken. I'll edit this if I ever find out how to make ""sphere"" formation do anything like it used to in Classic. Desired function is for the selected units to form a sphere around their order target. Presently, it seems to make them stop and pick their noses. ""X"" works fine. ""Wall"" seems to make plusses. ""Claw"" is okay. The Interface for move has been modified for ease-of-use, and this has caused a small amount of frustration. Right-click as well as ""M"" invoke the classic style move pie but right-clicking the out-of-plane height indicator for a pocket of resources issues a direct move order to that location and height (helpfully to save you from pressing shift for height changes or frustratingly when you were trying to invoke the move pie).Definitely recommended if you're still reading this far."
76561197999935899,Recommended,244160,16865648,"Posted: 3 July, 2015",all,pondrthis,"TL;DR: Overall, this is a good-looking update to a good-looking game, and is worth the money despite numerous gameplay changes that will demand a reworking of classic strategies. (If you absolutely can't stand the changes, play Classic Mode!)-----Homeworld is one of those games I would buy five times. Its story, music, and gameplay are all extremely well executed, and as a whole, the game is deceptively deep. The incredible art has been updated to look brilliant at the resolution I played the game (2K). I can't comment on the porting of HW2, as I had never played the original.There are numerous differences between Remastered and Classic that should be noted, though, some more obvious than others. Here's a list of changes that I felt notably altered the game's experience--I'm sure there are more, but these are the most notable:-Strike Craft don't use fuel. I would have preferred them to be buffed and still use fuel, but c'est la vie.-There's a limit of 14 Salvage Corvettes, which changes the Bridge of Sighs level significantly.-The issuing of some orders has changed dramatically--one click Scuttle, odd Kamikaze behavior, etc.-Evasive Tactics has been replaced with Defensive Tactics, which no longer causes Strike Craft to weave around attacks.-You can't create custom formations, effectively breaking Cloak Generators and Defense Frigates.-You can't play as the Taiidan in the campaign. I always saw this as a meta-story, showing the cyclic nature of the exile and painting the ending in a bittersweet light. So much for that theory.-As expected, ""Homeworld (The Ladder)"" was removed from the ending scene due to licensing costs. No more Yes T.TEven with all these changes, it's still SO worth it ^.^"
