,Recommended,244160,17206427,"Posted: 24 July, 2015",all,Skipjack Tuna,"I picked up this game during the Steam Summer Sale of 2015 while craving  a good RTS and I write this review having only played HW1:R with no plans to play HW2:R in the near future.I had heard great things about Homeworld before the remastered edition was even announced, echoes of praise for its story and gameplay. The high point of this game was the story, while not too in depth, it was good enough to keep me going. The combat, which is the crux of this game due to it having minimal base building(you build research ships and resource collectors, but everything revolves around your motherhsip), which I hear has faults somewhat becuase it runs the HW2 engine in HW1 was a little underwhelming. Entering battle can take quite a while and control over who and how your units attack is poorly executed. It can be difficult to be quickly precise where you want to send units due to the 3D nature of the map, and because of this some maps are flat out boring. One mission has you dodging and destroying asteroids before they can hit your mothership, and if you decide to use your bombers to take them out about half of your bombers will kamikaze(which is a seperate action you can order them to do) by accident into each asteroid. This game is not without its bugs, but as of my review it seems that the majority of them are patched.Needless to say the AI is a little underwhelming, and some missions poorly executed. Planning to capture enemy capitol ships and succeeding can be rewarding. Overall, thanks to the story and acknowledging that this is an older game with only a graphics touch up it stands up well today. Worth the sale price. 7.5/10"
,Recommended,244160,17207047,"Posted: 24 July, 2015",all,Kirutal,"I've been a fan of the Homeworld series since I was a kid, purchased the Game of the Year edition, still sitting proudly on my bookshelf with its Silver Clans Description & story books, along with its sequels. Hearing about the remastered edition, I nearly screamed in excitement because the game is long overdue for a refreshment, and I'm happy that I bought it.(JUST THE REVIEW OF THE REMASTERED HOMEWORLD CLASSIC, NOT 2)Okay, details now:What I like about the Remastered Edition of Homeworld (aside from its obvious graphics) is the new UI. It's much cleaner and is easily accessible all on one screen without actually visiting the 'Build', 'Rearch' & 'Launch' pages, which are now converted to panels. Having said that there are some downsides to it: I cannot click the 'B' key to quickly close my 'Build' panel, likewise with the 'Launch' panel, but only works with the 'Research' panel. It's not a huge problem, but it gave me a feeling that the remastering was rushed, rather than tested.Secondly, I don't like the unit ships display on the lower left corner, that in itself is more appropriate for Homeworld 2. I much rather have the Unit Ships of the Homeworld Classic, originally displayed on the top right corner for easily monitoring how many ships I have left in the game. It doesn't matter where it's displayed, I could care less, but having Homeworld 2's UI for Unit Ship Display in a Homeworld Classic where it's Build Per Ship, not Build Per Group of Ships, is annoying. All I see are just colorful outlines of  random ships in a non-scrollable display, with my assumption to myself, ""even though I built 30 Interceptors.... maybe I have 25 left? Less? Idk?""Sound can be glitchy, where ship chatter is close to non-existent, or I'm dealing with persistent ship engine noise all game, even when I pan far far far away, and docking is the only option left for me to get rid of that painful white-noise.And now, capturing ships with Salvage Corvettes doesn't intern them into my ships, they get recycled, and now I'm stuck with more minutes into each stage of the game just rebuilding them, because if you know anything about Homeworld, it's this: SALVAGE SALVAGE SALVAGE = BIGGER ARMY.So there are more Cons than Pros on the Remastered Collection, however that being said, I'm still a proud supporter of the game and the series, I just wished that the Remastering did some more gameplay testing before launching. Now I'm just sitting back and hoping that there will be updates to the game."
