,Recommended,244160,14792266,"Posted: 8 March, 2015",all,Whizzard,"When I was a wee little lad, my first experience with Homeworld was Cataclysm. I enjoyed it immensely and to this day I wonder how could I beat it at the age of twelve. Of course when Homeworld 2 came out, I played it into bits. But I never played the original Homeworld.Now, finally I got to experience it, well not in original form, but as remastered form, imported into Homeworld 2 engine and prettied up. And it was great. I played both campaigns of remastered games from start to finish and had a blast. While I understand that with the transition to the newer engine some of the original functionality of HW1 was lost but it never stopped me from enjoying the Homeworld 1 part of the remastered game. Everything functioned and it was a blast to play. Oh and how pretty it is. Really. I think I killed several hours just oogling at the pretty visuals and exploring every ship model inch by inch.However, the Homeworld 2 part of the remastered collection is nigh perfect. While the ship models may not have gotten the same amount of attention as HW1 remaster got, they still look stellar and with the extra modern graphical options, I got even more oogling hours of it. Oh and the campaign of HW2R is just as hard as I remember it to be. When you finally beat a mission that was giving you a real hard time the feeling of accomplishment is real. I love it.As for multiplayer, not all is well there but that's why it's still in beta. The combined HW1 vs HW2 multiplayer needs more work but if you strictly stick to playing Kuhsan vs Taiidan or Hiigaran vs Vaygr, you will have a good time. You also have a good time with playing the races of HW1 against HW2 but it can feel unfair at times, especially when HW2 ships are fully upgraded. But Gearbox is hard at work balancing the races out, so by the time it exits beta it hopefully will be as fun as the rest of the collection.And if you really really want to get that Homeworld 1 feel back, it is included in the collection in it's original form.Also, missing from the package is Cataclysm but... I don't personally miss it that much. If it's one day remastered, great, if not, meh.Verdict:  Beautiful, plays well and has great value as a whole package. I definitely recommend it to anyone who has interest in experiencing the Homeworld universe and I really recommend it to Homeworld 2 veterans as for you there is nothing wrong with the remastered collection.PS: You can find on community hubs that people have had issues with bugs, glitches and crashes but I personally never encountered any, except in multiplayer. Few crashes while joining a multiplayer game and one case of AI controlled opponents being forever idle in a players vs CPU match."
,Recommended,244160,14792464,"Posted: 8 March, 2015",all,ebeneezerdahk,"As a Homeworld fan, I cannot help but recommend other people enjoy the spectacular visuals that Homeworld Remastered offers...However I was extremely disappointed by the sheer number of bugs in Homeworld 1 Remasterd of which I have just completed my first play-through! (haven’t played HW 2 Remastered yet - intending to play through Cataclysm again before)The sheer quantity of bugs in HW 1 Remastered is bewildering, and where as I didn’t encounter any truly game-breaking bugs I had to change my strategy to work around the problems in game.Its fair to say, that HW 1 Remastered is NOT the same as the original HW in game play terms due to these bugs.To name a few in no particular order:* The removal of Evasive tactics and the way tactics affect the speed and attacking power of all ships (WHY??!!?)* Ships set to passive tactics still aggressively attack other enemies they haven’t been instructed to attack, you have to Stop (S) or Move them to prevent them from continuing to attack (pressing passive tactics again does nothing)* Formations do not work, ships to not keep in formation when given instructions...* When sending some small ships to dock (with Mothership or Carriers) they fly off to the left or right and continue ""into infinity and beyond!""* Sometimes the move command just doesn’t work, press M nothing, symbol on cursor appears but it won’t do anything, same in Sensor Manager view* Sphere formation no longer forms a sphere around ships being defended or attacked, ships just clump-up into a ball (and get Rickrolled)* Credits roll, and there is some poor sod's name is blanked out due to a drawing of a ship dropped over his name* Final mission has a seemingly impassable invisible wall preventing your advance (tip: go around the side)* Cut scenes showing the Exiles on their epic journey from Hiigara to Kharak has my ships floating around with the Exile colony ships* Repair ships now have to close to 0 range to perform a repair (same as capture range) - these ships also seem particularly susceptible to getting confused and doing nothing (Loved longer range repair in the original game.)* Missile Destroyers cannot be told to bombard an area or mines for example* Cloaking is broken, without any enemy sensor units on the field, enemies see and attack cloaked fighters and lone Cloaking Generators* Capital navigation AI is abysmal, will refuse to move at all if another large ship blocking path, gets confused when assigning formations (takes forever to move into position, and not JUST due to the speed of large ships)* Capital ships with multiple turrets (Heavy Cruiser in particular) does not focus fire correctly (with side cannon in particular)* Bombers and light fighters seem far less effective against heavily shielded targets than in the original, I cite Mission 6 Diamond Shoals as evidence of this, don’t bother using bombers, defenders or any small ships in that mission is my advice (dock them or move off to the side).* Another note on Mission 6, small ships love to suicide against the asteroids, funnily enough the large ships Frigates and above do a better job of avoiding the asteroidsThere are probably other 'FEATURES' here I haven’t listed, the above are the main points that spoiled my enjoyment of HW 1 Remastered.My advice to others would be to hold off on playing until the fix some of the fundamental flaws such as formations, tactics and movement bugs.All in all a visually spectacular but disappointing game play experience.What the heck were the QA department doing, they certainly weren’t testing the game... With Remastered having been announced so long ago I find it difficult to believe these bugs were due to release scheduling???Thank you"
