,Recommended,244160,14996841,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,Crypter,"If you haven't played Homeworld before, this an excellent place to jump into the series. This game is a trailblazer in real time strategy that no one copied, not even Relic themselves. Adding the third dimension to combat really opens up possibilities for ambushes, feints, and mobility. I hope that this remastered edition will inspire other developers.If you have played Homeworld 1, and you prefered it to Homeworld 2, then there's some things you need to know:The new graphics look gorgeous. The sounds have received a much needed overhall without changing their core essence. They definitely do not fall into the George Lucas Special Edition trap of too much remastering.But they've ported over the Homeworld 2 combat into Homeworld 1. Aggressive tactics no longer mean ""Go for long strafing runs and do as much damage as possible"" but instead mean ""Attack something if it comes into this radius."" That's a pretty big difference, since Homeworld 1 was very much built around deciding whether to sacrifice bombers for strafing runs.I assume they'll fix it at some point, but when I first played Homeworld 1, fighters tended to crash into ships an awful lot.I'm sure others have mentioned it, but the Yes soundtrack for the credits is missing, presumably because Gearbox couldn't get the rights. I was never a fan of Yes, but that credits sequence was really appropriate for the game.But yeah, if you like real time strategy, please play this game."
