,Recommended,244160,14724614,"Posted: 2 March, 2015",all,Tatsuhoshi,"Homeworld and Homeworld 2 were the best real-time space strategy games ever made.  Every game made since then has tried to be them, and has fallen flat by comparison.I am, however, still on the fence about the remastered versions of these games.  While they are graphically beautiful, without a doubt, a much needed upgrade to the visuals of the game, there are some differences in the missions, interface, and unit actions that I simply do not like.The first thing that cheesed me off with the first game was the interface change.  While the interface for HW2 is, technically better, they changed unit behavior to match.  This is a huge problem when you assign a bunch of units to guard something important, put those units on sphere formation, and rather than surrounding the unit they are guarding and forming a ball of guns around it, they just sit there beside it in something akin to a circle and not being the defensive line you were expecting.  This is more a glitch than anything, because this tactic worked fine in the orignal HW2 (it was just harder to implement with the interface changes), and does not work at all in the remaster.Some of the missions are very different from their original versions, making them much harder than they used to be.  There's a mission where your warp coordinates are incorrect and you warp into a moving asteroid field.  This is where I would normally turn into a wall of guns in front of my mothership, but aggressive tactics doesn't work on the asteroids in the remaster.  In addition to this, you are in the asteroid field longer than originally, so you have to prevent damage to the mothership for a much longer period of time.  This may not seem like a major issue unless you've already built several super-capitals and warp into the mission with 6 destroyers, each a fourth the size of the mothership, and these are getting taken out because they will only shoot the rocks you tell them to and it is impossible to defend them and the mothership from damage, leading to huge attrition and losses that were pointless.Homeworld 1 and 2 were already challenging games.  There was no need to make it more challenging.  There was no difficulty selection back then.  Games had to be an acceptable challenge level right out of the gate with a smooth transition in their difficulty from the beginning of the game to end.  Putting players against BS odds is not making a game harder, it's making the player face BS.  There is a difference.  Don't believe me?  Play the first 8 levels of the original game, and then play the first 8 levels of the remaster.  Something will feel different and off.  While it may be prettier to look at, it simply won't feel as if you had as good an experience as you did the first time.For those of you who never played this game when it first came out and felt the disappointment of games that just weren't as good that followed, you are about to enjoy one of the greatest games ever made, whether you are playing the original or the remaster.  Perhaps I'm simply jaded from waiting for similar games to even compete with this one since the death of Sierra with no good alternatives.  Perhaps my expectations are too high.  I don't know.  I will still recommend this game a million times over any other space RTS.  Relic and Sierra, I salute you for the awesomeness that were the originals.  Gearbox, I salute you for attempting to live up to the originals."
