76561197978782798,Recommended,244160,14692345,"Posted: 28 February, 2015",all,Corvus Dove,"Homeworld.  10/10.  That's the easy part of a review on Homeworld.  Just itself.   Yes.   Instead of giving a basic review, I'm going to compare and contrast the Remastered edition with the originals.   I haven't played Homeworld II RM yet, so this review is subject to update.   For brevity, we'll call these ""HW"" for Homeworld Game of the Year edition (1999) and ""RM"" for the Remastered version.  Also, Multiplayer is not reviewed here.*****HOMEWORLD 1*****1. Audio.  HW has always been known for its amazing sound and haunting music, and the Remastered version doesn't disappoint.  The missing highs and lows that made sound ""watery"" (due to early day sound compression) in HW are entirely cleaned up in RM.2. Graphics. HW's graphics have been heavily upgraded in RM, but the concept of using low polygon count models has been preserved; this is to prevent graphics problems in some truly huge battles, but mod makers may want to upgrade these further.   The textures used are beautiful and give the game a polished feel.3. Fighter tactics.  HW gave you direct control over fighter behavior.   You could choose Passive, Aggressive, or Defensive stances.   RM has this as well, but it doesnt' do the same thing.  Setting to Passive caused them to enter evasive maneuvers that could hold together a group of fighters that ran into a Missile Destroyer.   In RM, maneuvering itself makes no changes; only combat behavior.  This makes missions like Sea of Lost Souls require a new approach.In exchange, fighters seem to be more durable and the annoying ""fuel"" mechanic that could cause a fighter to be stranded in space has been removed (they work HW II style now).  This is itself a major change, as the Kadeshi Swarm (you'll know it when you see it) no longer requires fuel pods to survive.  They still exist to work as Support Frigates, though.   That completely changes how to approach the related mission.4. Capital Ships.   Capital ships seem a little weaker to bomber attack than they used to be, which is somewhat welcome.    They also move slightly faster and you don't need the same cloud of them that you used to in order to accomplish things.5. Difficulty.   HW took a unique approach to both cheaters and to people who had remarkable ability not to lose anything; the more you have, the more enemy ships will be in the next level.   This meant that cheating to add 90 Ion Beam Frigates or getting that many in the mission Bridge of Sighs turned the next level into hell.   You were encouraged to keep a small and manageable fleet but could go epic if you wanted.  This was handled differently in HW1 vs. HW2; it's now all using the HW2 formula.  This means the Kadeshi swarm is far easier than it was, and that if you are overpowered by the time you hit Sea of Lost Souls you are greeted by 30+ Assault Frigates.6. Formations.  Edit: Formations don't work once combat starts; the pilots fly like they are in HW2.  They're pointless and even cause problems.  Formations were once a major part of tactics in this game. Hopefully this will be fixed.7. Fleet Size.    RM implements the Command Point mechanics from HW II and severely limits your fleet to a realistic size.   Captured ships count toward the limit as well.  Great for continuity but you will recycle a lot more captured ships.The enemies seem to be limited by resources and their own Command Points now as there aren't as many of them in many scenarios, and it's possible to simply outlast the opponent into starvation by eliminating resource operations.8. Salvage Corvettes.  These get a special spot because in HW they really made the workhorses of your fleet, capturing half of your enemies and making them allies.   This is still true, but with some caveats added for balance.   Love them or hate them, they're there.A. Ships at a higher ""mission level"" than you seem to be uncapturable. An example would be Mission 3; any assault frigates captured in this mission are instantly converted into RU.B. Destroyed capital ships higher than Frigate class now leave salvageable debris.   Resource Collectors and Salvage Corvettes both can get them.C. No mass salvaging, you have to pick the right number of SC's and pick one target for them.D. Your defense fleet will ignore a ship has been captured if they were firing on it and continue to fire until it has been salvaged.   This causes a lot of ships you wanted to steal to get nuked.  This is hopefully going to be fixed in a future patch, as it vastly reduced the number of ships one can capture in an up-close fight.9.Special Abilities.   It was a common tactic in HW to assign a group of ships with a ""repair"" ability to something you want repped every time it is damaged.  The way to do this was to put them on Defensive stance and assign them to Guard the target.   In RM they don't seem to catch on that this means repair the target if it gets hammered; even a Support Frigate will instead fire its little pea-shooter at the attacking enemy.   Once the target is repaired, they will need another repair command if it gets damaged again.  This means micromanaging your repair fleet.   Hopefully this is a bug that will be fixed.On the bonus, some ships have new abilities.   The Scout, for instance, has a Speed Boost ability for getting out of trouble.  Dont' expect it to use it, however, without your command.10. Other changes.   One of the most notable changes from HW to RM is that HW gave you a choice between playing the campaign as the Kushan or Taiidan fleet.  You played the same role, but as Relic had no idea what gold it had on its hands when it made HW, they never expected to sequel, so canon was not a thing.  Whichever side you didnt' choose became the bad guys.   RM doesn't offer this choice, nor does it offer ship color customization like HW I does.   You will be the Kushan (which is canon) and the ship colors will be blue, white, and gray (also canon).If you are a fan of some of the old ""nifty"" things that ships did in HW1, you'll find those missing from RM.   The Kadeshi Multibeam Frigate does not roll when firing and its beams are now triangulated.   The swarmers dont' do jittery motions anymore.   Things like that.The original HW UI has been replaced with the HW II UI in RM, giving control continuity and allowing you to control manufacturing without losing sight of the map.   You can also issue move and attack orders from the sensors manager, which used to be exclusive to HW II and Cataclysm.Cataclysm is not included in this purchase.   It was not developed by the same developers as HW I and HW II and is only semi-canon.   The actual source code for this game has been lost.   It's my hope that a retelling of Cataclysm in a more canon fashion comes about as the next step in how Gearbox capitalizes this IP."
,Recommended,244160,14717812,"Posted: 1 March, 2015",all,lakku,"This is one of the best RTS-games ever made.I didn't remember it was this hard & deep learning and strategy. If you love a good RTS with great ambient feeling, amazing soundtrack and exciting gameplay, this is it. The remastering is amazing, no crashes and so on. Perfect launch.There's no base building, only resource gathering. This game is also about trial and error so you will lose missions and have to retry.After so many years I still got chills on the first mission cutscene. Go buy it now, what the hell are you waiting for?10/10"
