76561197969782921,Recommended,244160,14702051,"Posted: 28 February, 2015",all,Flatline,"It's Homeworld, with shiny new graphics. The ultimate space RTS. If you never played it the first time around, you need to buy this; the gameplay was never ever beaten, the story and mission variety is truly excellent, and the art direction is unique.If you *have* played it before: BE WARNED:At the moment, some of your favourite features from Homeworld 1 are rather broken. Formations, for example, do not work; your units will ignore them in combat completely, so no more flying balls of death with the sphere formation. Considering how a prominent a role the formations played in the original game, and how a simple formation switch mid-battle could turn the tide, this is a major issue, and one that really shouldn't have made it out of testing.Also, remember how you could capture all those assault frigates on the third map? Nope. Not anymore. Due to Homeworld 2's unit cap rules, you cannot capture a ship if you don't have the capacity. And you don't have the capacity, if you haven't researched it yet.Additionally, there are a few general bugs and AI mishaps, such as pathfinding being a bit dodgy (telling two support frigs to heal your ships will result in them bumping into each other and often allowing the ship to die), and engine sounds hanging (so you can hear a ship's engines really loud no matter where you are).In other words, in spite of the word ""remastered"", don't expect this to be *polished*. It's great, because it's Homeworld, but it needs some patching.That being said, despite having to launch the campaigns separately, the skirmish mode allows all content; you can play Homeworld 1 fleets against Homeworld 2 fleets if you want. Which is fantastic."
