76561198045943749,Recommended,244160,14741599,"Posted: 5 March, 2015",all,Mr More Dakka,"Make no mistake- this is very much a remastering of JUST Homeworld 2, with Homeworld 1 elements thrown in (And Homeworld 1's full complement of campaign and skirmish maps as well). You could say Homeworld 1 has been Shoe-horned in depending on who you ask given the effects of Homeworld 2's engine on a LOT of the Homeworld 1 stuff.(Formations collapse the moment combat begins, strike craft and corvettes all now act under Homeworld 2's parameters regardless of faction, harvesting and repairing both require direct-connection between ship and target regardless of faction, research now always costs resources regardless of faction, and other changes Homeworld 1 fans might be turned off by. These are all changes that most likely won't be reverted, as they're probably more engine-based issues than design choices.)So if you're a hardcore fan of Homeworld 1 who either missed Homeworld 2 originally or absolutely hated Homeworld 2... Then stay away- as Homeworld Remastered will most likely only frustrate you.  (OR buy it for access to the classics... But if you're a hardcore fan you probably have the disc version- which honestly isn't hard to get running on Windows 7. Windows 8 I'm not as sure, but I haven't heard of it being much harder.)Barring that? Homeworld Remastered is a worthy return for the series and does its job well: it honestly makes me excited to see what Gearbox will do for the (hopefully) eventual Homeworld 3. They put a lot of effort into this- and its not just the graphics that show for it.The skirmish/multiplayer modes are definitely where Remastered shows its differences from Homeworlds 1 and 2 the most- and is the point where most of Gearbox's effort comes to the front. As much as Homeworld 2's engine might 'tarnish' the Homeworld 1 factions- the addition of them and Homeworld 1's maps spices things up considerably. You'll have to re-learn the homeworld 1 factions, since their balance is now completely different, but they match interstingly with the Homeworld 2 factions.And then there's the AI- at least on Expert difficulty. Homeworld 2 suffered from having incredibly boring skirmish AI- especially compared to Homeworld 1 which actually had some excellent skirmish AI. In terms of quality, Homeworld Remastered's AI falls squarely in the middle- not as good as Homeworld 1's, but practically stellar compared to Homeworld 2's original AI. It definitely seems that Homeworld Remastered's AI is based off of Homeworld 2's original AI- but Gearbox clearly put a lot of work into improving it.So even though Homeworld Remastered is MUCH more Homeworld 2 than Homeworld 1- its still quite recommendable overall."
