,Recommended,244160,16253030,"Posted: 7 June, 2015",all,RyokoMocha,"These game are awe-inspiring, breathtaking, epic, majestic, and altogether outstanding is only barely adequate to describe the Homeworld series.  I have been playing them consistently since 1999, when the first game originally made me catch my breath in wonder, and the very first thing I've done upon getting every new computer since then has been to install Homeworld 1 and 2 and test them out on the new hardware.   Even if the gameplay wasn't as incredible as it is, the graphics and animation of the games would still make them worth playing, and even if the graphics weren't as spectacular as they are, the grandeur and scope of the story would make it worth following along to the end.  But amazingly, the simple yet intricacte controls, the joyous gameplay, the stunningly beautiful visuals, the angelic music, and a story worthy of ancient Greek epic poetry are all equally amazing, complementing and complimenting each other to create a whole greater than the sum of its parts, and the parts are so incredible that this is an accomplishment worthy of masters.  This is the Homer and Shakespeare of video games.The original Homeworld was amazing, with compelling graphics just abstract enough to feed the mind the perfect amount of information to create an impression greater than what was actually presented on the screen, the perfect method to create a spectacular effect despite the limited capabilities of the computers of the day.  Homeworld 2 was even better, taing advantage of a few years worth of increased computing power to make a game that gave me the initial impression of an actual cinematic experience.  The Remastered version takes those increased visuals of Homeworld 2, applies them to both games, and improves upon them even further, adding such detail that you can see the actual gunports and cannon on the fightercraft, Resource Collectors actually trail billowing clouds of vented excess gasses when they are full, and every craft has blinking running lights.  The full effect is such that the actual in-game, real-time animation is on par with, if not better than, the pre-rendered CGI visuals of '90s television shows such as Babylon 5.I cannot recommend these games highly enough.  I consider Homeworld and Homeworld 2 to be among the very best video games ever made, equalled only by Castlevania: Symphony of the Night and perhaps Metal Gear Solid.  Everyone who has any interest at all in commanding a fleet of starships needs to own this game.  Actually, that isn't right... everyone who owns a computer should have these games.  For those who truly want the full experience, I highly recommend researching online for the background information about the Kushan and their epic story as told in the booklets that came with the 1999 Game of the Year Edition (if you aren't fortunate enough to possess actual copies) and then you will understand why their journey is an epic of religious proportions.Buy this game."
