76561198016042569,Recommended,244160,15070231,"Posted: 26 March, 2015",all,uraki,"Visually, this game is an amazing update of the original. There are some minor mesh issues with salvage; single sided faces and the like can appear to disappear but this is a minor thing and does not interfere with gameplay.  I find it hard to play at a strategic level since you want to be as close up to the individual ships as possible and admire the work put into them.  Since modding has been part of the design, I can't wait to see what the community develops.Because Homeworld 1 is utilizing an updated version of the HM2 engine there are some changes to gameplay in HM1.  Exampes: hyperspacing in matches does not maintain the tactical formation of your ships.  Repair frigates no longer repair multiple ships, it must be selected and directed to one ship at a time.  Certainly nothing that breaks the game but does modify strategy if you're familiar with the original.Sound is great, it's just as wonderful and immersive as it was when it first came out.I do wish i could run the game full screen. I currently run Nvidia Surround (5760x1080).  The game does support that resolution and there is no real performance hit for doing so.  However, several parts of the HUD are elongated horizontally and cutscenes are resized to fill the screen width.   Also turns into a lot of screen to cover in order to get from one side of the UI to the other.  In a 1920x1080 environment there is absolutely zero issues.  I do very much like the ability to scale the UI.The Remastered Edition is a wonderful update for those seeking nostalgia.  For those new to Homeworld, I think you'll find a beautiful RTS with an interface that's easy to use and a very modest learning curve."
