76561198047169453,Recommended,244160,14670335,"Posted: 26 February, 2015",all,DeinonychusCowboy,"Loved the original Homeworld - truly a classic RTS, and one of the best space-based RTSes ever made.This remake has MASSIVELY improved the graphics over the original - this isn't a touch-up of the game engine, the entire game seems to have been ported to an updated version of the HW2 engine, with more detailed models, beautiful visual effects and lighting (Bloom, HDR, and depth of field! DEPTH OF FIELD, in an RTS! You can tell how serious the visual style of this game is.), and a lot of mechanical similarities to HW2. The game looks very modern; it does not look like a game that was concieved and created more that 15 years ago.However, the developers clearly worked very hard to keep the feel of the original game alive. The model detail may have shot up remarkably, but every ship looks like its original model, seen through a clearer and sharper lens. From a distance, the models are the same; close up, there are more little lights, windows, and intricate polygons. Every new ship I see is literally jaw-dropping; the amount some of the ships have improved is incredible (the Turanic ships really stand out at this early point in my playthrough). The gameplay is almost unchanged from the original - I've played HW1 so many times that most of the missions are second-nature to me, and my favorite strategies still work perfectly. There are no unpleasant surprises or head-scratching design choices; the only noticeable departures from HW1 are either immaterial (Resource collectors behave more like those from HW2, essentially docking with asteroids, but have a similar graphical effect to HW1, the big sucking beam of ionized resources), or awe-inspiring (a certain spoiler-laden cutscene in Mission 3 is all the more shocking for its terrible beauty).The difficulty and balance seems to have been tweaked somewhat. I distinctly remember the first several missions of every HW1 playthrough being very resource-sparse; you had to maximize every RU and soon learned exactly how much you could build and when. The remastered version is more lenient, likely because (like HW2), research now costs resources as well. I have also found myself building more fighters to replace lost ships than in the original. However, some of my least favorite changes from HW2, like enforced squad sizes, were thankfully not carried over to the remake, and gameplay staples like dust clouds were brought back. Everything works the way I expect, and there are nice surprises, like the fact that capital ship explosions leave debris in a similar manner to HW2, that enhance the original gameplay. Overall, the game feels a bit easier, with the areas of difficulty being slightly different from the original and more like HW2. However, I don't think the shift will offend long-time players of the game. It's not as though the remastered version is not challenging, and I don't think most of us play the game for its difficulty curve. The strategy, story, graphics, and mechanics are more important to me than how many times I have to reload Mission 3 because a single you-know-what was vaporized.Thus far, my only major disappointment has been that Homeworld: Cataclysm was not included in the remaster. Though I know it was not generally considered canon, and was developed by a different company with no input from Relic, it was my first Homeworld game, and I really enjoyed the storyline and some of the gameplay additions it made to the already very addictive HW formula. I think HW:C would make a great game even with all the references to the Homeworld universe removed, and I would love to see it redone in this new engine in a similar manner to HW1.Great remaster, great game, worth the money in 1999, worth the money today."
