76561198007145952,Recommended,244160,17229367,"Posted: 25 July, 2015",all,Arcterran,"Hoo boy this is going to be a long one!  I played the first one back when I must have been around 13 years old, AND LOVED IT! Played the second one a while later and liked it but it didn't quite do it like the first one did. That bias is probably never going to go away but I'll do my best.Gearbox has been nice enough to package the originals in case:A) Your computer can't run the remastersB) You are a HW1 PuristC) You liked a bunch of HW2 Mods that haven't made the jump to Remaster yetBecause of this, this is going to be THREE seperate reviews (HW1 Classic, HW1 R, HW2/Remaster), since HWR, HW2, and HW2R use the same engine.Lets Talk HW1 Classic first.Homeworld 1 Came out in 1998 and blew minds for being an RTS that allowed for Full 3D control and you could effectivley re-enact the Battle of Endor from Return of the Jedi.My take? It's a legend, for good reason. Granted age has taken it's toll on this (Notably low-ish framerate, and some poor UI decisions that do make things harder to execute at times), but it is still a brilliant, Micro-oriented RTS with emphasis on Unit composition and formation management.Essentially all ships have a set amount of manuverability, and some ships have better turret coverage than others, while other ships (Fighters, excluding defenders and Taiidan Defense fighters, and Ion cannon frigates) can only fire forward, in a normal RTS this may be a nightmare to properly set up, except for one single mechanic, formations. Formations allow you to take full advantage of your fleet by arranging them in a pattern. Be it the claw formation which is a great offensive formation for fighters and corvettes as they envelop their prey, sphere for defending your resourcing operations, or an imposing wall of Capital ships to focus down other ships in quick succession. Knowing what you have and adapting your formation tactics is key to winning fights in HW1. Granted unit composition does a lot of heavy lifting too, but it does play a signifigant factor in combat.It also has what I feel how story SHOULD be handled in gaming. Most of the story happens to you, and conveyed through in-game scenarios. The worldbuilding is fan-freakin tastic, with some genuinley unsettling set pieces, beautiful use of Adiago for strings (I still tear up every time it's played), and of course, THE GALAXY ACTUALLY FEELS LIKE IT'S TRYING TO KILL YOU! It's not a terribly complicated story, but it'll hit you in the feels, not to mention the writing is top notch.Also you have a persistent fleet, meaning your resources, tech, and surviving ships carry over into the next mission. It's a neat concept and fits nicely into the story they were telling. Plus Salvage corvettes, those things are awesome.Speaking of, the interim mission cenematics are quite stylish, basicaly animated concept art with some voice over in the background, it's a style relic will be known for (Company of Heroes comes to mind).Also special mention to the tutorial, it doesn't progress until you get the mechanics and are ready to advance, then throws you into a small battle just to make sure.Of course it has some issues that got worse with age. For one, in many missions (especailly a lot of the earlier ones) the strategy is to abuse triggers so you builld a strong enough fleet to take on the fleet you know is coming (Since they ambush you the first time), and then activate the trigger. This also kills quite a bit of the pacing, since construction takes FOREVER when you are building a fleet (not to mention the sluggish post-mission resource gathering).That said, there are plenty of missions that don't follow this, and the best ones are those where you have to think outside the box, or are thrown immediatley into a battle.Secondly the UI isn't that great. It's servicable, but it's got issues. Mainly due to the fact that to access anything pertaining to construction, research, or docking, you HAVE to go to a different screen. It wouldn't be nearly as bad if Homeworld wasn't so dang micro-oriented, to the point you are constantly monitoring somewhere between three to nine different control groups, depending on how you set things up. Plus selection I find can be a bit finnicky, as well as issuing orders if you aren't careful.Now with that out of the way let's Talk HW2/HW2ROn the upside, HW2's engine vastly improved the UI. There are sidebar tabs, that allow you to access anything that at first took you to a different screen. Plus Issuing orders is stupid simple now. Albiet a little too easy as you can click on game objects and the ships will move towards them, so you still need to take some care where you click.Also the pacing in the single-player campaign is better. You are typically always on the move, and resources are automatically gathered at the end of each mission, however, missions now end automatically, so you won't have much time to prepare for the next mission.That said, the story is considerably weaker, it ignores some established canon (Three great hyperspace cores never sat well with me), and there's this very generic ""Save the homeworld!"" story going on. That said the Vagyr do put up a great fight, they are an interesting faction rather than a mirror faction, and the guy who did Makaan couldn't have done a better job with his acting. Just...the Vagyr don't hold up to the Beast or the Taiidan Empire (or anyone else you fight in HW1 for that matter) in terms of a villan you'll remember.Not to mention formation management is mostly gone (except for fighters, which change formation depending on tactic, which was seperate in the first, Remastered 2.0 Fixes this, see the HWR section) which is a bummer, though admittedly it is more fun watching squads of fighters come out than single file.So let's talk HW:R, It uses HW2's engine but with HW1's campaign.So you get the better UI and pacing (you actually Auto-collect resources, AND can build a fleet to your desire before you hyperspace out) not to mention Gearbox's art team made both HW1R and HW2R Drop dead gorgeous.Fuel management is also out of here like it was in HW2, so you don't need to constantly dock your strike craft (fighters and corvettes). I welcome this change actually, as it removes downtime from your fighters which were kinda underpowered in the first game regardless, and gets rid of some, honestly, needless micro.EDIT 6/8/16: THEY FIXED FORMATIONS! Though they work differently from the base game. Now when you select formations the game auto selects ships and groups them up and splits the selected ships in several ""Combat groups"" that use said formations. So far I like it but I am dissapointed in losing something like a Giant sphere of Strike craft protecting my resource controllers. For the Record HW2 fleets works like this too, except they still retain the ""Squadron"" mechanic.I'm not going to talk too much about Multiplayer since A) I only played one match and B) it's in beta hence, still in active development. Other than it's really neat to see HW1 fleets fight HW2 fleets, even if HW 2 fleets overpower HW1 fleets for the most part.Last thing I'll dive into is Mod support, It's fantastic, My personal favorites are the Halo-themed ""Homefront"" and ""Tactical fleet simulator"" which is a balance overhaul mod that makes pretty much every ship useful in some way (and they add a whole bunch more). Albiet most of the mods are old HW2 mods re-uploaded onto steam, and the creators are still waiting on some updates so they can properly port the HW2 mods to HW2R, and it's glorious high-res coat of paint.Also as an aside, I found it quite difficult to find tutorials, which is a shame, I kinda wanted to mess around with it. Though a knowledge of LUA is required.So yeah I reccomend it, it's a great deal at 35 bucks, I honestly think Gearbox did the best they could, given the engine conversion from HW1 to 2."
,Recommended,244160,23151407,"Posted: 22 May, 2016",all,sdmblack,"If you expect a game similair to more mainstream fare like Age of Empires, you will be out of your comfort zone here. I know I was. Honestly, it is an incredibly complicated game to excel at, but it is impossible for it to be any other way. You have complete control over every unit, with 360' movement in space. This is important because every unit has a different defenses and attacks, with some only being effective from certain angles, allowing a cunning opponent to take out your forces with surgical precision if you are not careful.The sound design is incredible, with the music and voices taking a backseat to the gameplay, but complementing it wonderfully. I can't claim to be a writer or a composer, but the atmosphere of the first few missions is nearly unsurpassed.The launch of the game was rather rocky, with many of the Remastered's features and changes being buggy and incomplete, but the untouched original versions are also included in the purchase so there was an alternative during the early days before these issues were patched.I have no nostalgic history with this game, and as of yet I have only played the remastered versions, so this is not an exhaustive review, but after playing what I have I can say that anyone looking for a more nuanced strategy game will likely be pleasently surprised."
