76561197992676928,Recommended,244160,31489445,Posted: 1 May,all,Space Monkey,"This is the first time I've played a ""remastered"" game, but after finishing the Homeworld 1 Remastered campaign tonight, I have to say that this most definitely isn't just Homeworld Classic with spruced up graphics and modelling. There is no doubt in my mind that Remastered is the version to get for someone new to the Homeworld franchise, but at the same time, for players that grew up with and loved the original, some aspects of the Remastered version can be jarring.Homeworld is the first significant RTS that let you use all 3 dimensions, and it's known for its strong story and interesting units. Remastered remains true to these roots, but it also takes lessons learned from later Homeworld games to try to make the original game more accessible and playable. The updated interface and units look fantastic, but Remastered is not without controversy because it tries to recreate Classic game mecahnics using lots of Homeworld 2 DNA, and while the results were generally good, not everything translated well. In the end, while Remastered is /similar/ to Homeworld Classic, there are plenty of subtle and not so subtle differences that make Remastered play like a strangely different game.Below is an incomplete list of the differences I noticed during my playthrough:1) Fighters are Corvettes are totally different. Fighteres seem to do less damage and are less durable overall, and you can no longer put them in a single gigantic formation. Corvettes don't seem to work as well against fighters anymore, but they seem to hurt frigates more.2) Formation size is no longer determined by the player...the game breaks your large selection into supposedly ""optimal"" sub-formations. Gone are the days where you can put 40 Ion frigates into a single imposing wall of death.3) Units tend to break formation, even frigates and capital ships. This bothered me quite a bit because my fleet didn't feel like a cohesive fighting machine as before.4) You can no longer re-arrange your units back into Military Parade formation.5) Depending on how you play, there are some scripting errors in missions. For example, I never got the option to research Multigun Corvettes in Gardens of Kadesh, and I had to finish the game without them.6) You need more Salvage Corvettes to grab capital ships...4 for a Destroyer, 6 for a Carrier or Heavy Cruiser7) The final mission seems to be buggy in terms of difficulty scaling. I started the Hiigara mission with 42 Ion frigates and something like 16 Destroyers and 5 Heavy Cruisers (salvaged from previous missions), and Remastered basically threw, on my doorstep, at least 60 frigates, 6 destroyers, and a heavy cruiser within 60 seconds of mission start. I'd lose my mothership in less than a minute because my ships with heavy guns start too far away to make it back to the mothership in time. The only way I beat the game was to retire 16 ion frigates at the end of Chapel Perilous.8) Probes don't spin in flight and the fully completed research ship is stationary too.9) Either the Assault Frigate or the Destroyer (I haven't figured out which one) will sometimes announce ""Flak Frigate heavily damaged""10) You get a lot more RU's in Remastered...In Classic, I never felt like I had a real RU surplus until near the end, but in Remastered, I had more than 20K by the 5th mission and I never gave a second thought to resourcing after that. The auto-harvest mechanic is also kind of funky...I didn't even bother sending resource collectors out in Supernova Station, but ended up getting 25K+ resources anyway.11) The firing animations are quite different in a bad way. There used to be a recoil effect on guns that weren't ions that even corvettes had...but in Remastered, the guns seem to go pew pew instead of boom. Watching ship combat up close just isn't as cool without the recoil effect.12) Frigates and Capital ships don't ""burn"" anymore...you do see some pretty cool looking hull damage but they don't vent plasma-like stuff anymore.13) The sensor manager view is prettier and more usable, but it's not as clear as the original...dust clouds are practically invisible in Homeworld Remastered but they were very much discernable in Classic.14) While you have the option to order strikecraft to kamikaze, the mechanic seems buggy at best. I sent 60 fighters to their glorious deaths but the enemy destroyer I targeted just shrugged it off."
,Recommended,244160,21467525,"Posted: 25 February, 2016",all,Cerv,"I played the original Homeworld back in the day, and it was one of the most epic games I ever played back then. The Remastered just makes it like 10x better. The visuals are amazing and the game is so smooth. Homeworld is probably the best RTS I've played, and I've played a lot of RTS. Pretty much everything about this game is awesome."
