76561197976493324,Recommended,244160,34412820,Posted: 22 August,all,Unctious Seaman Pawkins,"Homeworld 1 (not reviewing 2, since I haven't finished it) is a mixed bag, but the pure joy I had when I was young(er) when I first played it makes it impossible for me not to recommend it unless you really hate real-time strategy games.  Even then, I'd still argue it's worth the experience even if you can't stand micromanagement, hot keys, and the stuff that makes a RTS a RTS.The fact is it's not always going to be pretty for the novice.  Battle plans tend to fall apart into chaos if you're not keen on grouping or micromanagement.  You certainly cannot take certain ships or your orders or lackthereof for granted in Homeworld!   With a bit of practice, you will coordinate an attack (or defense) with a bit of finesse, and you will fill the void with an array of colorful explosions.  Nothing quit as satisfying as taking apart a heavy battle cruiser and harvesting its left-overs.  (Harvesting resources in this game is probably one of my favorite features - it's just so cool to watch the ships go about their business!  Homeworld: Space Miner!?)  The first play-through (especially without a guide) might get downright ugly, but Homeworld is overflowing with charm and the passion of its developers both past and present.  It's a beautiful game, to say the least.  (If you have a nice 4K monitor, I believe you might need to wear protective eye gear.  It looks good on my little ol' LCD.  It's hard to not be impressed with the work they put into the textures and fx.  This game wasn't ugly by any stretch of the imagination, but to have a game from 99' look competitive?  Nice work.)It's a tootin' shame there's no replay function - that I'm aware of - built into the game?  (Maybe multiplayer has it?   Zooming in on the individual ships and formations is where it's at!) It's one of those games, like most RTS, where you're tasked to do a lot of stuff at once.  Positioning in a three-dimensional space in the void of space is awkward, and the grouping and fleet formation design is better/more polished than the original.  But, IMHO, it's still a bit confusing and difficult in the heat of battle.  I know what I want to do with my ships and how I want my strategy and attack to develop, but excuting it with a keyboard and mouse is what it is.  I would say it's part of the inherent challenge in all popular RTS, so it's hard to fault the game for asking you to anticipate and plan a few moves ahead.  Know thy hotkeys.  Some are better at this keyboard magic/micro than others.  I find keeping the ships moving helps as it's surprisingly easy to lose a ship or forget to designate the proper orders.  (I can't tell you how many of my salvage corvettes (boarding ships, basically) took a leave of absence during a mission.  C'mon, seriously guys?  Get to work!)  I also found myself frustrated during a couple of the more difficult missions, but thankful for the challenge.I think the biggest key to this game -  at least my enjoyment - was the story, music and sound direction. (I believe they actually brought back some of the original voice actors for the re-master.) This game just reeks of a space opera waiting to be made again and again.  Is there every a shortage of sci-fi?  I hope not!Hope you enjoy it as much as I did when I was a kid.As a side note:  If you make a mistake with your resources or the type of strategy you employ it will mean starting over or replaying an older save game.  Worst case?  Strategy guides are plentiful.  (Luckily, it's not a horribly long campaign, so not a big deal if you decide to go in blind and DIY.)  So, be prepared, and always save, save, save!"
